Bakal's tenant: The poeles are warming, he has signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man walked out the door of the RPG Byty customer center of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying under his arm a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and that of his son who is serving a sentence.
The deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of the second category 4100 crowns.
"And there's no hot water and the heating works on solid fuel," the man with the signing power shows on his son's new contract.
"But I signed anyway," he explains to angry and half resigned.
The citizens' association of apartments BytyOKD.cz, which described the renting conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a leaflet will be published to explain the method to follow to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a gesture of his hand.
"One says that, the other says something else" by frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory for deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic expect whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
For this reason Aktualne.cz has decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
A single press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You do not have time to read your number "157" as your number already starts to light up on the large screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a short moment, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems like everywhere else - requests for repairs, insurance events and the like.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mails with new leases in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The new rentals special counter has been open to the public since November 18.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still a trial," the employee behind the counter responds after a moment of hesitation when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Derailment and the old apartments of Bakal miners are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of the parliament and from the Ostrava region Lubomir Zaoralek of the social democrats reported this fairly consistently before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
"Twenty years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change a plank put in the toilet, the man mentioned is relieved in introduction.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to make sure they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised RPG in a special offer.
This is a discount of half the amount of the rent that will be received by other tenants who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" counter on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by questions.
“Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent,” the employee told the counter.
And yet RPG porpos both on its website and in the windows of individual interviews on rents when it is necessary.
If the two parties do not agree on the rent, an independent court will decide.
“It’s not about threats, it’s just about informing you about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,” RPG said on its website.
“No one will go to court here,” one of Byty’s RPG employees thinks, and the man on the street in front of the customer center is right.
“I have 13,000 retirement crowns and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don’t have enough to go to court,” he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and so people are waiting,” she said.
The regulation of rents ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and the increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the fund for housing," says Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the fund for housing that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in the rent.
However in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this is expected to make 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered chairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no fewer than 31,200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.
"And it will always be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," the screen reads.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really very low sum of 19.66 Czech crowns per m2," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices that included the architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected that it also houses a mini kindergarten with everything you need - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch. design employees have been able to visit.
The company of projects-architectonic Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini business kindergarten from the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
She employed about 90 people, mostly of child-bearing age, and it was important to her that women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
At the same time as reduced-time work contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
This gives builders and architects the opportunity to combine work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund through the Human Resources Operational Programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding (to the tune of 2.8 mil.CZK). They were able to buy equipment and equipment and after two years ensure a qualified staff as well as the start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project took a year and it was the Economy rating company that helped to make the request for staffing.
Childcare is provided by qualified staff, all day a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children. children can go to kindergarten without age limitation but they are over three for the most part.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more that replace.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school without looking at the hierarchical position.
Although it is about individual care and education, the mini kindergarten program is comparable to that for preschool education.
The children do not only play there but quality teaching is also ensured - from the beginning to the preparation for school benches English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and not have the stress of a delay in picking up the children at a school far from the parents' workplace.
Parents use their time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus listed among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi’s interiors.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric Saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic shapes, the house received the nickname Bone House from locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, are all ypical for Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation one sees the geometry, the rhythm and the order thought precisely.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of bright colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood in waves copies the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the eyelet and the slats.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district on the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction took place over two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on demolition of the old construction and construction of another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-family home was not thought by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were born.
For the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the house hot just after its finish because of its organic shapes "the House of Bones".
Others, given the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "the house that gives way".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its time of central heating, with vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems weird.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not respect the building directives of then and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction it obtained the building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data carried on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for changes.
For example, the city council members did not like the fact that the pillars of the construction work on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's call, Josep Battlo asked for (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of linking spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or else limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction has received away from new facades a non-traditional roof and two more floors.
Gaudi’s play with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with skylights.
The two-color play gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark which, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house which was inscribed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the tours as they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the field of tours to common areas and attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance price for Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
