Devices to track people are increasingly demanded by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases as for example that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a match box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they began looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage, but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The children's psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to carry something of this kind on him, he will get rid of it.
“And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long waits,” says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very questionable.
"If this is a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will do everything possible to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
“Currently, it’s the phone.”
“As soon as tracing equipment develops, they (criminals) will look for it as well because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign.”
"In such cases the criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits that such devices can help in an unprepared assault by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracing services for both cars and people, having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The apparatus may be configured in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period."
“In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned.”
“More expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is lying down without moving,” says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart cell phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special software.
The problem with current tracing systems is that it is either a device similar to those that are worn on a pendant the size of a match box or to smaller telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that’s why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracing device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracing cars.
It is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
The army has so many detonating cords that it could go around the Czech Republic with, but it can only last two years.
