To this day, I am taking advantage of the contacts I have obtained through the competitions.
The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun for the place of winner of the contest for the best Individual Entrepreneur.
The winner of last year’s Best Individual Entrepreneur competition was 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukas Pytloun.
His adventure to success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun loved to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Liberec there was a lack of a quality accommodation site at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned while working abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a student in his third year of higher education, it was a courageous action.
"The ratio of quality to price of accommodation in our area made me want to do something," says Lucas Pytloun.
He began to rent the first rebuilt apartment to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profit in the building which he converted into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his activity as an entrepreneur has allowed him to open in Liberec 4 pensions, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of almost 300 beds of all accommodation categories.
The most comfortable of them was until very recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year another one of the same quality happened to him.
“We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other Pytloun hotel franchise candidates showed up,” the number one contractor said last year.
"And for the sale of the license for the operation of a large-scale hotel, the victory in the Entrepreneur of the Year competition served well," Pytloun adds with gratitude.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in Liberec and its surroundings.
“People recognized me on the streets, congratulated me often and, I must say, it was very pleasant,” he recalls.
He recommends participation in this contest to anyone who strives to do something.
There is no need to win, but any opportunity to be visible is good.
He says he is still using his contacts and knowledge that he could not have otherwise obtained.
“With those I met through the contest, I started to have regular business relationships.
According to him, the fame related to success has also had an impact on employees.
And he's about 70.
"I observe in them above all the loyalty and pride of having committed themselves to something that has been generally recognized."
"This is not, by far, the only result of my personal work, but the result of a good work of all of us together.
"Only my name is pushed forward," says Lucas Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successor a better year than we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the winner's sense of purpose Farmet has the worst moments behind him.
The one who came to Slovansky dum for the first place in the Vodaphone Firm of the Year competition last year is Karel Zdarsky, the owner of Farmet.
The jury rewarded the efforts with which it transformed a tool shop in Ceska Skalice into a firm with a turnover of 100 million crowns.
"I can say that the award has not only encouraged me and my employees and increased our self-confidence to fight the competition," said last year's winner.
At the beginning of the history of the company Farmet there was the desire to do something useful.
And so when the state offered Karel Zdrasky’s father to rent the small workshop as compensation after the communists confiscated the property, he did not hesitate for long, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with a few comrades in his father’s entourage for the manufacture of plastic bathtubs.
Not long after they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
After eighteen years, it became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company was known even in the non-specialized public after the success obtained in the competition through the media.
“Not only did our customers really get to know the Farmet brand but also the foreign partners who started to realize that they were collaborating with a company that had the greatest success in its home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year has not only been spent in Farmet in the euphoria of victory.
The company's assessment was based on the economic results of 2008 and partly of 2009.
And in 2009 it was the most difficult year for the sale of engineering machines.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect citizens, companies were forced to stop their investment projects and begin to limit their purchases of new materials and technologies.
"Obviously we have not escaped this situation."
“The turnover fell by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even lay off,” says Karel Zdarsky.
A viable society must know that unpopular action is needed from time to time.
But they managed the situation correctly and retained beneficial results even if they were inferior to those they had before the crisis.
At Farmet, however, they continued uncompromisingly investing in research and development.
"We built a training and research centre with the grants, strengthened the company's presentation in international exhibitions and won the main awards in national exhibitions," says Zdarsky.
Everything suggests that the crisis is behind them.
The numbers of Affires go up and with them the number of employees as well.
"To the new winner I wish that pleasant feeling of victory but in a calm atmosphere," says Karel Zdarsky.
The investigation that removes senseless regulations.
The Inquiry into the Absurdity of the Year is for the fourth time a part of the business clan.
