Households will pay an additional 100 kronor per month for housing.
Starting in January, households will have to pay a supplement not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
As of January, families will have to pull out of their wallets up to a hundred crowns a month more than they do now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some places you will have to pay up to a tenth more for the supply of water and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 kroner per annum for households in apartments.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the significant development to encourage the manufacture of renewable energies, including photovoltaic batteries.
The gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the highest consumption.
One can also count a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest communes that are planning to increase prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 kronor more per month, families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 kronor annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation for the event that the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the Prague will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are rising by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will increase significantly, for example, in the 450,000 apartments for rent from January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2,500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided on an increase of up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be brought to court by the company.
The regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase by 10 percent next year.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very gently.
The fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from the parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of physicians encountering cases similar to admissions in the children's departments of hospitals.
“Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk.”
"The trend is really towards strong alcohols," says Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at the Horovice hospital in Central Bohemia.
“When they manage to chip a bottle of dad in the closet, it’s sometimes about whiskey but it’s fernet and vodka that predominate.”
"Vodka has the advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it," says the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, a spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, said she was right.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
“It’s alcohol in fashion today, especially in elementary schools.”
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought home from the house," Jurinova added.
According to the head of the Pélikan department, seeing drunk children aged 13 to 14 years old at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced for ten years in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide surroundings completely drunk.
A girl was hospitalized four times.
"She started her career at the age of twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood, plus a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
“What’s interesting is that it didn’t seem weird to the mother that her daughter was away for 48 hours,” the department director said in a statement.
It is the disinterestedness of parents or their extraordinary tolerance in the face of the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, we do not talk about addiction, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the term alcoholic we mean a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that we do not find in children."
"For those who use repetitive acool, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-family background," explained the head of department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunken children were hospitalized this year until mid-November at the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with a crave intoxication requiring hospitalization are integrated into the statistics.
Drunken children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or the police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pélikan, there are three seasonal waves with which one can count: Witch's Day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after poor results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"Of course I experienced the Witch's Day admission of seven drunken children at once," Pelikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in medically controlled detoxification is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffered the day after the "hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have an excellent evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re just astonished at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils patients’ good mood at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Transportation by ambulance and hospitalization on intensive care bed can go up to tens of thousands of crowns.
“Once in a while, I have applied this as a means of education by counting to these children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they could spend the whole summer on seasonal work to pay for a single night,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their regressive managements, which should recover from parents the burdens related to care, do not deal with cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two L-159 aircraft of the five in all, for which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were until now in service in the Czech Army and were in a flying state.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seater versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the company Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defence, the physical departure of Vodochody's planes is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for the exchange were taken on long-stored aircraft without causing additional burdens or investments for the Ministry of Defence."
"The two-seater L-159 T1 has been exchanged in the state," said Pravo Pejsek.
In May 2009, the ministry signed an agreement with Aéro Vodochody worth 200 million crowns for the conversion of four unused L-159 cars into two.
The military took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introduce the aircraft in the equipment of some countries of the Alliance.
“The contract clearly states that the one taking into account the L-159 aircraft is EADS and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore the case of the one who considers how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not launch a tender and contacted EADS directly.
At the time, the defence management argued that the exchange ensures future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought from Aero Vodochody 72 aircraft and uses only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft is likely to have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen as part of a European-wide tender and in no case directly contacting a manufacturer.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
Longer index than annular index is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than the ring finger are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This can depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under the age of 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo the prostate cancer test, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index finger shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular the risk however fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60 the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
