Americans have a new "smart weapon"
The U.S. military has sent a new "smart" weapon to Afghanistan, known only as the code name XM-25.
The generals believe that this new automatic rifle will have an influence on the conflict there with the Taliban and "will change the game" for their benefit.
The new weapon is like a super accurate gun
Its projectiles are guided by laser with a precision of a few meters.
The special ammunition of 25 mm caliber developed for this rifle and containing a highly explosive breaking, in fact functions as small grenades.
The ammunition can be programmed in such a way that it will explode in contact with the target but also at any point in their ballistic trajectory.
It can therefore be used against an enemy who hides behind an obstacle, a wall or a ditch.
It is also not protected from above and when a deadly rain of steel chips falls on it, it can also put it out of combat.
According to Richard Audette, who took part in the development of the XM-25, the new rifle is the first infantry weapon that uses “smart” technology.
"The soldier essentially uses it in such a way that he finds the target, sends it a laser beam that determines the distance, thus obtains a precise point of sight, according to which he corrects his site sighting and presses on the trigger.
"Let's say you've targeted at 543 meters."
"When you press the trigger, the weapon loads and shoots at a distance of 543 meters plus or minus 1, 2, 3 meters," Audette said.
400 relocated jobs
The Fujitsu Group relocates its subsidiary from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
Next year in July, 400 employees will transfer to Astro Park their workplace, which is currently located in the office building on Mareinbader Square in the Bad Homburg region.
The Japanese Fujitsu Group relocates its branch from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
As the giant specialized in the manufacture and maintenance of computers said on Wednesday, next year in July, the workplace of 400 men and women, located so far in the Marienbader square in the city of Bad Homburg, will be transferred to Astro Park, a huge office complex located on Lyoner Straße in the Niederrad district of Frankfurt.
A spokeswoman for Fujitsu said that in the medium term, the group is expected to bring together another 100 jobs still scattered so far in the region.
The rental offer was extremely attractive, and the open-air offices at Astro Park are better suited to the way employees work.
In Bad Homburg, too, Fujitsu was just a tenant.
CEO Bernd Wagner said: “Frankfurt-Niederrad is a prime location with a remarkable infrastructure for us.”
He says that the connection to the airport is of great importance for a global company like Fujitsu.
The new move of a major company inside the region yesterday sparked the joy of the winners and caused the disappointment of the losers.
The Frankfurt City Council’s head of economic affairs, Markus Frank (CDU), said once again that a “global player” had been conquered.
It is an "extraordinary profession of faith relative to the place of implantation".
Fujitsu is suitable for the city and its location is an important momentum for Niederrad.
The mayor of Bad Homburg, Michael Korwisi (the Greens), regrets Fujitsu’s decision.
At an early stage, management informed the municipality of this intention.
"It goes without saying that we have offered our help to this company," Korwisi said.
However, the friendly relations could not have changed the difficulties of the computer manufacturer facing the owner of the Marienbader Square building.
In the end, the economic reasons would have been decisive.
It is now a matter of preventing such an exceptional place from being unoccupied for a long time.
"I hope that the owner and landlord of the building will be cooperative."
Ten years ago, the City Hall Square building, previously used by the Fujitsu company and the neighboring "small vertical" as well as the rest of the Marienbad Square buildings, were part of the controversial spa construction project.
As a result of a joint project of the municipality and a private project developer, a new entrance to the city was created between the station and the City Hall, which aroused a lot of criticism, not only because of the impressive layout of the areas that used to be partly parking, but also because of the height of the buildings.
In 2001, the rating and investment advisory firm Feri, the computer manufacturer for travel distribution systems, Start Amadeus, as well as Fujitsu, a computer manufacturer at the time still associated with Siemens, moved into the buildings.
In 2006, the German Frankfurt-based specialty group Immobilien-Chancen bought the buildings occupied by Fujitsu together with the Morgan Stanley real estate fund, and a year later these buildings were resold to the Spanish company Falcon Real Estate Investments SA based in Madrid.
The Fujitsu Group, headquartered in Tokyo, considers itself the third largest supplier of IT products in the world.
For example, it makes computers and servers available to businesses and also provides the essential service.
Its branch in the Rhine-Main region is one of the largest in Germany: Fujitsu certainly has much more employees in Munich.
The branch, Fujitsu Technology Solutions, leaves Bad Homburg to move to Frankfurt-Niederrad. The other subsidiaries on this site are Fujitsu Services and a company named TDS.
For this, 7,000 square meters have been rented in the Astro Park building.
This 20-year-old complex, whose name is reminiscent of its star-shaped design, is home to, among other things, the headquarters of the Confederation of the Electronics and Electrotechnical Industry.
Expulsion of the server by Amazon - Threats against Mr. Assange
WikiLeaks is facing more and more problems.
Internet service provider Amazon has expelled the site that specializes in revealing confidential documents from its servers.
This attitude may hide political pressure after the publication of hundreds of thousands of secret diplomatic notes.
WikiLeaks founder Mr. Assange is apparently staying in England.
In the United States, the WikiLeaks website is being attacked with ever greater force.
The cyber-activist group "WikiLeaks" no longer has access to its server hosted so far in America and is now looking for a host in Europe.
Meanwhile, eminent U.S. Senator Joe Lieberman has called on other countries and companies to boycott WikiLeaks.
And WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange, who is wanted by Interpol, is likely staying in Britain, according to reports published by newspapers.
"Wikileaks excluded from Amazon server."
"Freedom of expression in the country of freedom," the cyber-activists behind the revelations said Wednesday via the social network Twitter.
Shortly before, the cyber company, Amazon, had removed WikiLeaks documents from its servers.
After the release of the secret diplomatic notes, the cyber-activists resorted to the Amazon Web Service (AWS) in order to reach the largest number of accesses to the documents.
WikiLeaks tweeted: “Formidable, our dollars are now spent on caring for the people in Europe.”
When free speech poses a problem for Amazon, “they should stop selling books.”
CNN, citing Liebermann’s office, reported that Amazon banned WikiLeaks from using its servers after the investigation by Senator Joe Lieberman’s collaborators.
The chairman of the Senate Committee on Territorial Protection had threatened the Amazon site to orchestrate a boycott against it, the British newspaper The Guardian reported.
“I would have liked Amazon to take this step sooner in light of previous Wikileaks publications of classified information,” he said.
At the same time, Liebermann called on other countries to refuse the use of the servers by the platform.
“WikiLeaks acts in an illegal, monstrous and unscrupulous manner, putting our national security at risk and endangering lives all over the world,” the statement said.
“No company aware of its responsibilities, whether American or foreign, should help Wikileaks disseminate the content of stolen documents.”
Wikileaks founder Assange, who is wanted by Swedish authorities on suspicion of rape, is on Interpol’s wanted list.
According to the London newspaper The Independent, the 39-year-old Australian lives in Britain and Scotland Yard knows exactly where he is.
The cyber-activist has consistently described as intrigues orchestrated by his critics the lawsuits brought against him by Sweden.
WikiLeaks spokesperson Kristinn Hrafnsson said in London that threats had been made against the site.
"Calls have even been made for the murder of Julian Assange."
That’s why Assange is particularly concerned about his safety, Hrafnsson said.
This is also why the founder of WikiLeaks continues to hide.
Hrafnsson clearly reacted to the statements made in North America.
In America, former Republican Governor of Arkansas Mike Huckabee has demanded that the person responsible for the Wikileaks revelations be prosecuted and executed for treason.
In Canada, Prime Minister Stephen Harper’s adviser told television, obviously ironically, that Assange should be “killed” and Obama could “use a drone.”
Meanwhile, a controversy broke out between the White House and Mr. Assange.
Robert Gibbs, spokesman for US President Barack Obama, called it "ridiculous and absurd" that Assange demanded the resignation of Secretary of State Hilary Clinton if she was responsible for the order given to diplomats, and recently disclosed, to engage in espionage activities.
“I don’t know exactly why we need to take care of the opinion of an individual who owns a website,” Gibbs said.
"Our foreign policy and the interests of this country are far more important than the claims of a website."
The US government is now fully testing the protection of its databases.
According to a White House statement, Russell Travers, deputy director of the Counter-Terrorism Centre, has been appointed as the official to fight the leaks.
Travers is in charge of putting in place "the necessary structural reforms" made indispensable after the disclosure of diplomatic cables by Wikileaks.
The White House also wants to verify the means by which the entire administration exchanges and protects information.
In addition, the U.S. government has announced that it wants to take care of the security of dissidents and activists if they are ever threatened by WikiLeaks revelations.
"We have made every effort to get in touch with them," State Department spokesman Philip Crowley said.
“We are ready to protect them if necessary.”
The University of the Ice
At the "Gelato University" in Bologna, ice cream confectioners are prepared for the best seasons of the year.
The three-day introductory course for future glaciers was very successful and attracted visitors from all over the world.
By the way, where does all the ice come from?
Glacier and ice machine.
The glacier, i.e. in German the somewhat outdated ice cream confectioner, makes the cream according to all the rules of the Italian art of making ice cream.
The ice turbine removes the ice cream from the refrigerated showcase using a spatula, disposes it into the waffle and then starts selling it.
To know, one does not need to go to Anzola dell'Emilia in the province of Bologna.
But anyone who wants to know more about the ice, can not avoid "Gelato-University" of the Italian firm Carpigiani.
The sorbet maker founded the University of Ice in 2003 so that the ice creams released from its machines everywhere meet the high Italian ideals.
The three-day introductory course for future glaciers was very successful and attracted visitors from all over the world.
There are also special courses on chocolate ice cream, which spans several days, and hands-on sessions are held in the private ice-cream shop.
In the midst of the crisis of their forties, a number of people dream of a new career, others simply risk fulfilling their burning desire on the smooth ice.
This time, 40 participants came from 19 countries from all continents, from Brazil to Saudi Arabia and Hungary.
Jacky, an art education teacher from California, is a fan of the Slow Food movement and wants to offer a quality European product to the industrial ice cream country in the future.
Anke from Berlin is a business management consultant and, after a few years, she wants to draw something unique from this nerve-wracking profession.
Two young Egyptian women dream of opening an ice cream shop in Cairo.
A man from Malta and another from Brazil would like to improve the quality of ice cream in their bars, and the Canadian housekeeper came because her children love Italian ice cream.
Master glacier Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal characteristics of perfect ice.
Determining not only the good taste, but also the silky flexibility and the good consistency.
However, Luciano does not forget during the training the cherry on the cake of the national superstructure and, in general, from the south: "Italian ice cream is simply the best: and then it still retains a fair dose of romanticism."
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees thanks to an electronic program, then immediately cools to four degrees.
He then opens a tap installed on the machine: he takes out a white cream of pasteurized base, the foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately beset with the question: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can one give free rein to the personal pleasure of experimentation?
Mr. Luciano cautions against being misled by the spirit of time.
Anyone who only talks about ice cream "made from natural ingredients" may have nevertheless used stabilizers: most often a natural product, for example guar seed flour obtained from guar bean.
It is obviously possible to make ice without using a stabilizer, only it must be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it will collapse and the customer will not chew anything but ice pellets.
Some modifications of the base mass are permitted.
It gets more exciting with the aromas.
Master Luciano makes the difference between the ingredients that are purchased in the fruit or confectionery shelf of the supermarket.
In addition, there is powder and pasta.
"Suppliers will all try to refill you with dozens of flavored ingredients."
"However, you should just try."
Either in the recipes of fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruits.
Either in ice creams made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs to it becomes a yellow cream and forms, when added cocoa powder, the basis of all possible desserts to chocolate.
Now, all participants in the course have to move to the use of ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla aroma or other natural ingredients.
The different types of fruit ice cream are also subject to the same experiment.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purees: from the point of view of taste, this is not absolutely better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily have the taste of walnuts, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
The kiwi ice cream, very popular, is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
"Only a balanced mixture correctly enhances the taste of an ice cream," says Luciano.
Ice making is a computational exercise: if you use peach puree with a lot of sugar, you need to reduce the amount of sugar in the basic recipe.
A supplement of sugar is needed for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents a device with which he determines the sugar content of the different types of fruit (winners use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, the tables make the calculations easier.
The production of ice no longer requires as much physical intervention as in the past.
It is not only the automatic base mass making machine that helps.
There is also an apparatus in which the available ice mixture is simultaneously beaten to make it creamy and brought back to negative temperatures.
Despite all the automations, slight failures are not excluded.
The Brazilian Gustavo brushes with fruit puree from head to toe and, thus, splashes his schoolmates when control of the colossal mixing bowl escapes him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that "such an incident is likely to occur in each class: it is only a matter of time."
Controllers in an Ambiguous Position
According to some sources, the industry that experiments with the cultivation of genetically modified plants has nucleated the European Food Safety Authority.
This accusation is now made by the Testbiotech expert group which is considered an independent institute for the assessment of the consequences of biotechnology.
“It sounds like a conspiracy theory, but we’ve been well informed,” Christoph Then, the director of Testbiotech, said in Munich on Wednesday.
Some reports indicate that the chairman of the Efsa expert group on genetically modified plants, Mr. Harry Kuiper, as well as other Efsa experts are under contract with the Ilsi lobby group.
It is funded by groups such as Monsanto, Nestlé and Bayer.
Mr. Kuiper has been instrumental in the development of EFSA's test requirements for genetically modified plants and is therefore clearly in a conflict of interest situation, according to the criticisms made by Mr. Then.
The provisions elaborated correspond, in paragraphs, to the positions taken by the Ilsi lobby and thus bear the mark of the industry which, in essence, would be controlled by the authorities established in Parma, Italy.
This is already the second time Testbiotech has denounced a conflict of interest.
A senior EFSA official has recently joined the Swiss agri-food group Syngenta unconditionally or without a transitional period. In doing so, She has changed sides.
Not long ago, even the Mitteldeutsche Rundfunk (MDR) revealed the existence of personal relations between the European Union control authority and the industrial lobby, which aroused suspicion from both the German Federal Environment Agency and MEPs.
However, EFSA does not accept the existence of any conflict of interest.
One opinion indicates that all reliable data, including industry data, is used as long as it is of good professional quality.
Experts working on behalf of EFSA are not prohibited from establishing contacts with this sector of activity.
But they should make them public.
Mr. Kuiper admits that he works for the International Life Sciences Institute, Ilsi, based in the United States.
This body sees itself as a neutral forum bringing together experts from, among others, science, industry and politics to assess the risks of biotechnology without being a lobbyist.
In this case, independent experts such as Mr. Then disapprove of the fact that genetically modified plants are accepted without any animal feeding tests and that the impact of these plants on the environment has not been tested.
"We want to know what, for example, the impacts of genetically modified maize are causing the field," says Mr. Then.
The current practice is to test only the isolated proteins and not the entire genetically modified plant, which does not allow reliable results to be obtained.
“If we don’t look for risks, how can we discover them?” asks Mr. Then in an accusatory tone.
This is also the view of Ms. Angelika Hilbeck.
She has been researching genetics since 1994 and is currently working at the Zurich Polytechnic School.
In this region as in the United States, and now also in Europe, the industry sector is increasingly trying to influence or discredit critical scientists.
For this reason, there are hardly any researchers who are not related to societies.
In the company's view, critical studies would not be published.
Ms. Hilbeck says that "the industry controls security research."
