Struggle for talents to conquer high potentials
The counter is very busy.
16 students are rushing to buy salmon rolls, tomato sauce and white-eaters.
The Technical University of Braunschweig and the car manufacturer Volkswagen invited design and mechanical engineering students to a workshop.
As part of a kind of idea competition, they have to talk business about the car of the future with the designers of VW, and, by the way, know the Volkswagen company.
Nowadays, many companies do not hesitate to go hand in hand in the competition to find better brains and to engage, like Volkswagen, in a multifaceted cooperation with universities.
Their mission: To recruit the most talented graduates as much as possible in the amphitheatres before they arrive in the job market and they are courted by others.
And since universities do not publish statements about the performance of their students, we try to identify outstanding talents in practical projects and to retain them.
On the second day of the workshop organized at the Technical University of Brauschweig the automotive group loves the talents.
A young lady from the staff department shares pens, candy and cards with the Volkswagen logo.
She talks about the schedule of professional internships and student jobs for young talents; she shows them the ways to access the group enclosure.
Nico Selle from the Technical University of Braunschweig is responsible for the project with Volkswagen.
For him, there are reciprocal benefits for both parties: "Students get in touch with this industrial sector and gain experience."
“As for the Volkswagen Group, it can get to know the students, take a closer look at the serious candidates and appreciate those who come into consideration as a collaborator.”
According to Mr. Selle, such cooperation is unusual.
What is new is the offensive with which we seek to attract students.
“In the past, the focus was on the professional project,” says Selle.
The struggle for the conquest of new graduates will become much more bitter.
In industry goods, companies can no longer recruit their employees by sorting out a host of candidates.
But they must praise their reliability and above all court the highly skilled workforce.
It is mainly graduates from engineering degrees who are in an excellent position to negotiate.
According to the German engineering association VDI, more than 40,000 engineering positions remained unoccupied in October.
And according to the forecasts of the VDI, the vacuum relating to the positions of engineer will increase further.
Roman Dykta goes on a talent hunt for KPMG, an audit, accounting and consulting firm.
It organizes expensive talent recruitment events, such as the KPMG-Race cruise race, a sort of paper rally where competitors have to find their way using GPS coordinates.
The company will send eight promising students next year to travel the United States in this way.
Participants can also visit KPMG subsidiaries and get to know the company.
Participants must decide in advance after two selection procedures.
Only the cream of the cream of the many candidates will fly to the United States.
According to Dykta, the means used to search for high potentials in universities are increasingly important.
"We want to emerge from the lot thanks to the cruise race."
"For us, a simple cruise was too little"
For the talent hunter Mr. Dykta, the count seems to be there.
"Until today, we have remained in touch with all the people who took part in a similar action last year."
"Some of them are about to finish their studies and want to send their requests to our company soon," he says.
Apart from the direct amalgamation carried out on campus, small and medium-sized enterprises proceed in a quite conventional way by participating in trade fairs where they engage in brain hunting.
"We are trying to reach graduates by participating in trade shows."
“For example, at the solar technology show,” says Sitha Stübe, head of human resources at Solarworld, a manufacturer of photovoltaic panels.
The Bonn-based company employs around 1,500 people in Germany.
Ms. Stübe is aware of the issue of succession.
Currently, 35 positions are contested on the company's website.
"At the moment it is very difficult to fill vacancies."
“It’s expensive and takes a lot of time,” he says?
Another way to establish contact is through university professors.
Solarworld has established cooperation with various institutions of higher education, for example the University of Fribourg.
"Professors indicate that the student has the opportunity to undertake professional internships or write his or her graduation project with us."
Expensive advertising campaigns are being announced by solar specialists.
This is why the company tries to advertise by highlighting other qualities: personalized atmosphere, flat hierarchy and easy communication.
“Often, a large group can’t do that,” says Stübe, chief of staff.
For a long time, money has no longer played the leading role in job search.
Other determinants are flexible working hours, childcare or good promotion opportunities.
According to a study conducted by the Great Place to Work Institute, Solarworld ranks 55th among the top 100 employers in Germany.
The institute is an annual honours table for German employers.
To this end, he asks employees about their degree of satisfaction with their work and its context while looking at the framework conditions of the employees.
The head of staff Ms. Stübe hopes that this placement will enhance the company's image among job seekers.
“I think candidates rely primarily on external assessments when it comes to a potential employer,” she says.
Wolf Reiner Kriegler from DEBA (Deutscher Employer Branding Akademie, DEBA) advises companies that want to build a good reputation as an employer by applying a long-term strategy.
He advises his clients to show more authenticity.
And, according to Mr. Kriegler, that means first and foremost taking internal measures.
“The best way for an employer to become attractive is to go through its own employees,” he says.
This is called, according to the jargon used in the sector, the internal image strategy, i.e. the creation of the employer's brand image within its own workforce.
"Satisfied collaborators make the best messengers."
When they treat their employees well and identify with the company, they advertise their employer to their friends and acquaintances on their own.
“It’s like playing in an orchestra,” Kriegler said.
Obama puts a brake on new oil drilling
There will be no new oil drilling in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Florida in the southeastern United States in the coming years.
The Washington government has issued an equivalent ban and thus definitively overturned its initial plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new drilling remains banned for the time being.
Home Secretary Ken Salazar made the announcement on Wednesday.
The explosion of the Deepwater Horizon drilling rig in April is behind this strict ban, which is expected to remain in force for at least the next five years.
In the face of this accident, which claimed the lives of eleven employees and led to the largest environmental disaster in the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and this sector of activity, had indicated that he was willing to authorize new drilling in the eastern part of the Gulf of Mexico.
The proponents of this solution want to reduce the dependence of the United States on foreign countries in terms of oil supplies.
The question of who bears responsibility for the devastating tide in golf has not, to this day, been definitively resolved.
The British oil group, which faces billions in claims for compensation, is at the center of the charges.
A commission of inquiry set up by Obama is due to present its findings in December.
In October, Home Secretary Ken Salazar lifted the freeze on the drilling site after the platform exploded.
As a result of this decision, various oil groups had immediately submitted applications for new drilling projects.
With tighter controls and tighter security guidelines, Obama and Salazar want to prevent another disaster.
The competent supervisory authority, which has discredited itself after numerous allegations of corruption, is currently undergoing extensive reforms.
At the same time, Obama announced they would eliminate the lucrative tax niches of gas and oil groups.
The players in this sector now publicly warn that the flow of feed in the Gulf would be significantly lower than it has been so far.
"The government's goal is to put a brake on the rapid growth of the oil and gas sector," according to a current survey conducted in the sector by the audit firm BDO, ahead of the drilling ban pronounced Wednesday.
In fact, the American Enery Alliance deplores the uncertainty that characterizes this sector: "No one knows exactly what will change with the regulation."
Investments in new support projects have been postponed until further notice, to the detriment of growth.
The Ogoni country is dry
The water flowing into the rivers is oiled brown; it gives off a odor similar to the one that exists in the gas station: Due to a leak, billions of liters of crude oil destroyed Ogoni country in Nigeria.
Humans live on theft, corruption and oil refining.
Celestine Akpobari has a good intention.
“Don’t get exhausted,” the environmental activist told reporters to calm them down: “You still have enough oil mud in front of the water lens today.”
The 37-year-old Nigerian has attempted to photograph a young man plunged into muddy water to the chest, as well as the greasy trail that surrounds him: This scene looks almost beautiful in the radiance of water in the color of the rainbow.
We cannot see that the basement is full of brown crude oil.
On the banks of the Bodo-Jetty River, Esther Badom recounts that she once collected shrimp in whole buckets here.
But in the meantime the calm waters have completely dried up.
Five years ago, a huge amount of oil erupted from an oil pipeline that exploded into the huge swamp.
Fishermen living in the small nearby town of Bodo must now row for six hours to reach the fishy waters: The Ogoni country located in the heart of the Niger Delta is considered one of the most polluted regions in the world.
The entire extent of the devastation is evident when you walk through the mangrove swamps crossed by streams.
Instead of clear water, the motorboat splits crading brown water, and anyone who dips his hand into it removes it all covered with oil.
The roots of small mangroves emerge from the ground like licorice sticks. The isolated palm trees sadly leave their palms hanging.
We search in vain for clouds of birds, as we usually encounter them in wetlands: As soon as the outboard engine stops, a ghostly silence descends on this paradise of yesteryear that resembles a gas station by the smell it gives off.
"What is happening here is war against the environment," says Celestine Akpobari with a sad look: "Our life is characterized by a permanent danger to health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The area where the Ogoni live is a besieged battlefield for decades: More than 60 years ago, the first European explorers penetrated here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by the writer Ken Saro-Wiwa, who was later executed. In 1993, the Shell Group had to interrupt its production activities in this region because these were very dangerous.
