Is the Splatter film an artificial film?
Director Nicolas Winding Refn explores the boundaries of the ancient genre through his film, "Walhalla Rising", the epic of the fighter.
What audience did Danish director Nicolas Winding Refn think of when he shot "Walhalla Rising"?
A Viking warrior (Mads Mikkelsen) possessing only one eye is taken prisoner; he frees himself from his executioner and, with almost supernatural force, eliminates his opponents one after another. This seems ideal for young male spectators to wait for dead in search of a bloody action, precisely because our hero uses brutal methods of assassination.
On the other hand, until the end of the film, the blind man does not say a word about his real name. Even the other characters let escape, at the most, by the detour of one or two sentences some appalling screams of agony.
Otherwise, nothing is said and we celebrate in the incredibly beautiful mountainous landscape of Scotland that is the setting of the Viking universe, about a thousand years ago.
This would be ideal for more mature filmmakers with an interest in existentialism and for excellent travelings.
When a film targets several target groups, it is a pity that they exclude each other.
The director Winding Refn is considered, since the release of "Pusher", his trilogy related to the fierce drug dealer and full of style, as a kind of Danish Quentin Tarantinon, but he refuses to bring a little more mood to the mainstream or introduce a little less brutality to the cinema of art and essay.
Most supporters of art cinema must experience horror in the face of the brain that spreads all around and to the intestines.
Lovers of action films die of boredom when the blind man boards, for reasons that can be freely interpreted, with a group of violent Christian missionaries on a ship bound for Jerusalem; they are drowned for an eternity by calm and mist before the crew arrives in America and continues to be silent.
It is not surprising then that "Walhalla Rising" did not find any distributor of films in Germany and that it exists only in DVD format.
It is mainly because of the magnificent images of misery that deserved some attention, but also because the image of a thrilling film, from time to time, hides behind a pretentious and bloody appearance.
It is not a matter of dialogue in this film, nor of a coherent action, everything is atmosphere, a feverish dream transformed into a film.
The spectator cannot escape it.
Refn barely gives him a moment of relaxation and slowly cuts his throat with glacial images and a gloomy soundtrack, but above all with an elusive hatred that springs from the hearts of the characters.
Only a young blond boy, who stands faithfully by the side of the blind, preserves a certain innocence, all the others are animated by anger.
More than anything, the blind hero whose motives are never known, but who returns from hell at any time to fight enemies and temporarily allies by transforming himself into a warrior, is perhaps sent by the devil himself.
It represents decay, but perhaps also, just for those who are, anyway, decayed.
"Walhalla Rising" is an enigmatic film that can be hated or admired, which aims at anger, enthusiasm and astonishment.
