The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications about a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
In the night of 5 to 6 September 2007 around midnight, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the Euphrates; the largest city located nearby is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
Its name appears in the IAEA documents, because it is talking about the reactor that Syria built with the help of North Korea in stone parallelepiped, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric current.
According to a briefing by U.S. intelligence services, the CIA, dating from late April 2008, the current reactor, known as the nearby town of el-Kibar, would be well-suited to produce plutonium, which would allow atomic weapons to be manufactured.
On the other hand, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video with fuzzy satellite images.
Through computer-aided animation, it indicated the probable location of each component of the reactor prior to the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the inside of it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be commissioned, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is barely more information available than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery is getting deeper and deeper.
Former US President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before this attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built a reactor in al-Kibar, but had little evidence that the country was developing an “active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more cautious about it and speak only of an “alleged reactor,” even though they consider the CIA’s presentation “plausible.”
They lack tangible evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he was dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior U.N. diplomat gave only a laconic response in the summer, saying the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions."
The Syrians certainly hastened to remove the rubble of the " unused military building" and proceeded to a methodical flattening of the terrain.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of man-made uranium in al-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received through a member state satellite images from commercial providers showing the moment directly following the attack; it appears that the latter are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity in an objective manner.
Syria has always assured that it had never carried out a secret atomic program and that it had not built a reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found on the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after analyzing the particles, calling it unlikely.
Since then, damas refuses any discussion about this, as well as about satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to conduct a second inspection at the al-Kibar site and refuses access to the wreckage of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel keeps a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister in office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on it."
For example, the investigation into this case has been dragging on since June 2008 without a result and is "increasingly becoming a serious credibility issue for the Agency", as acknowledged by a senior Western diplomat serving at IAEA headquarters in Vienna, ultimately a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
The IAEA believes that to make progress, it is necessary to clarify the existence of the other three facilities that must have "a functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated which facilities are here, what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "Süddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively as Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also by the names of neighboring cities.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington has identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that is most likely one of the suspicious objects.
It is possible that it is located in a military base or directly next to it; that is exactly why Syria denies access to the three sites to IAEA inspectors.
In Vienna, Syrians are said to fear that the inspection group is actually spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it was intelligence provided by U.S. secret agents that drew the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A high-ranking Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could “serve for fuel production.”
It would have "no indications of sensitive activities", such as enrichment and reprocessing of uranium; processes that are essential for the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible assumptions about the following fundamental questions: where should the uranium have come from and where would the plutonium needed to make the bomb later have been separated.
It is not known whether the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, was stored in the three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with dirt have disappeared, no one will have information on where the rubble will be stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that in 1998 Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located just a few kilometres from al-Kibar, across the Euphrates River, examined to see if it could be suitable for the storage of radioactive waste.
By recently analyzing satellite photos taken on behalf of Jane's Intelligence Review, former IAEA Inspector Robert Kelley has established a link between them and the reactor in question.
Satellite photos show, however, that Syria undertook earthworks at the three suspicious sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those sites.
It may be a coincidence, but it did not help to dismiss the suspicions.
