Many Haitians, including many who were displaced by the January earthquake, were wandering around the neighborhood to find where to vote.
Some of them eventually gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favorites, denounced the fraud and demanded the cancellation of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the senior official in Haiti of the United Nations, considers the event to be "a pretty good election in many ways".
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that they "did not believe that these serious irregularities necessarily invalidated the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, is due to announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The second round is expected in January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
