But there may be problems if Mr. Celestin, who has little or no noticeable support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority to have reached the second round.
With an epidemic of cholera raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, it was feared that participation would be.
At the time, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards, required to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are important.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And so, it is clear, the Haitians do it themselves.
