Prosecutors will not indict Senator Ensign
Attorneys for the Department of Justice have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign over a case involving a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get lobbying work for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers said on Wednesday.
The ruling puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Ensign's office said he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer being investigated and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice abstained from commenting on the matter.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, saying there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, obtain a lucrative lobbying job to gain silence from Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's case with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as Treasurer in a Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator with Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole for a year.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to contradict the so-called lobbying revolving door ban.
“There appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and materially violate the revolving door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the Ensign decision, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop the prosecution of former Senator T. Steven's fault.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the general manager of citizens for accountability and ethics in Washington, a defense group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's senior lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the ministry was not seeking charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice except to say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign's parents' payment of $96,000 to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Home Office on a matter in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after he hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth-ranking Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
