"This case," they wrote, "represents that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can civility bring divisions closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as about recognizing their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the committee on the president’s deficit was just as civilized, despite the political divergences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of requirements or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties are miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed in tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade.
That's good."
On certain issues, especially those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism lies on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed widespread skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between now and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the tea voters who contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in early reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the toughest tasks in Washington and, according to them, have imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there are, at least today, few reasons or willingness to compromise on tax issues.
Galston plans two phases in the battles between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care, and then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Whoever will be judged as a loss will have to change course and find compromises.
However, this would be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
US documents leaked describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocracy" and passes to the Kremlin some of the bribes and protection money it collects, the U.S. Embassy in Russia said in a note in February.
Police and the Federal Security Service are conducting huge racketeering that helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the “vertical of power” – takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been purged.
It was written while Yuri Luchkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for the corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has been little clearing since then.
Loujkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have always denied corruption charges over the years; and he has won several defamation lawsuits on those charges.
In September, he told a Russian television station when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's thrown away, it's anything."
The Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information contained in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be for diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link established between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people to call it "dysfunctional" and claim that the government functioned more like a kleptocracy than a government, according to the embassy note.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term used in the criminal/mafia world which literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor’s office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
“The FSB, the MVD and the militias are on the second level.”
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas where the city does not provide certain services.”
The report states that the FSB is robbing the money of the largest companies and that the police are targeting the small ones.
One source, he said, “explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because not only do they have more weapons, more resources and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law.”
“That’s why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer so high.”
The note notes that although the collection of money is extended, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly see their business shut down under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but he has admitted that little progress has been made.
The note from the embassy conveys reports of men bringing suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
“In his fight against corruption, Medvedev is dependent on bureaucrats,” said Georgi Satarov, director of Moscow’s Indem think tank, in a recent interview.
“But he’s part of that bureaucracy.”
“It is not part of a political class because there is none in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption are estimated to be more than $300 billion a year across Russia.
The country was ranked 154th in a recent poll on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked at least as corrupt).
The release of the note from the US embassy, which was only made yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, will certainly stir up discontent within the Russian government; although Loujkov may be blamed, to some extent, for the failures of Moscow, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed by CNN by Larry King, Putin hypothesized that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fabrication and reacted angrily to the remarks that U.S. diplomats had disclosed by calling him Batman and bringing Medvedev closer to Robin.
"The problem is that this is our interaction, an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he said.
“But to be honest with you, we didn’t suspect it would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to ethics.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit classroom with decrepit concrete walls of poor quality, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School spoke about the man who built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader; and he cared about his people,” said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty to Anlong Veng is finally called into question.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led with the United Nations, handed down its first sentence concerning a former Khmer Rouge member, sentenced to 35 years in prison, the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch".
Faced with this development, anxiety has increased among Khmer Rouge veterans from Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"The situation creates divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the U.S. Pol Pot government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia’s border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large Khmer Rouge fighter groups began defecting from the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the Khmer Rouge veterans have plunged into black misery, common to rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officers retained their positions of local leader in exchange for laying down arms, they were unskilled farmers at low rank and record.
“These people benefited from very little follow-up after the capitulation,” said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They are soaked in the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime.”
“They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept.”
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Ta Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to provide for our own needs.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge tribunal has also caused concerns here.
The court is expected to begin the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, early next year.
The court’s mandate is to try senior leaders and those responsible for the crimes, but it did not say whether it continued beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm fears at Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation turned to 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers were reportedly killed.
Recently, on a hot evening, Im Chaem was returning from work to the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
“Cambodia is at peace and stable,” she said.
"If there is more prosecution, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court sued several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang of the documentation center.
“Reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces,” he said.
“We need to put these pieces together so we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved handbook on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history textbooks of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, a 19-year-old student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new handbook helps students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he came home with the book to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court,” he says.
“They are suspicious because they don’t know exactly how many people the court will sue.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retains a powerful appeal here.
In the heights of the Dangrek mountains, a path, invaded by weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads up to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cell phone seller, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many inhabitants go there to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day she planned to walk to the last resting place of Pol Pot where she would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in hopes of bringing luck.
