On the contrary, this is another restriction on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, nearly 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal rigour, fines to countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments of one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and it has been defined for a long time, so now there is no room for apology.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first signal of divergence between what Germany thought needed to be done (fiscal rigour plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow from the Central European country was when Merkel hardly prolonged the decision to save Greece.
From that moment on it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to make possible the rescue of a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear a part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European because it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although slightly sweetened, was approved, and in the following months we should see the process of reforming the Union that makes these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we do not agree too much, from then on the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that violate the rules will be severely sanctioned, they may be forced to declare themselves in cessation of payments and, in this case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a question of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked to do is much harder.
And what he should absolutely not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring us greater tranquility.
And let us know how to seize the opportunity we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with the big companies and the announcement of yesterday's new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, the path has been opened to the thesis that it is necessary to put the house in order.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to move it.
And among the possibilities envisaged, one cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too full of unreasonable countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it has warned us.
Sport and Fraud Law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate the ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused a lot of ink to flow about the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the game (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, both players will carry out the regulatory sanction during the next game of the playoff against Auxerre and will be able to move without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Discipline Committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not quite common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case related is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his hymn displays the nobility and honor and who in past occasions sentenced to a fine to its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, it seems, by Mourinho, who provoked his story and added an episode of more trinic to his di.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation and contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions are a fraudulent act, because they are indeed actions that respect the sporting regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of harm they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has not been a violent game.
Another of these assets that are alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the offending team from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating o fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action has precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders get from the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same game either, because obviously the result of the action implies leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club could not count on these players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a sanction match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing up the ladder, it is not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which nevertheless includes the making of strategic decisions that promote the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), but otherwise they chose rather the time in which they submitted themselves to it.
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or escaping it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-evictions and because of the way to transmit the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
