The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
Individuals must go to Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to show up at the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASCs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain benefits for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for visa processing and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visas will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken from the CSA, applicants who wish to have a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
