A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
In Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n, the United Nations proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that is nearly one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorescent compact bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (LEDs), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of global fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will have to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance sheet to stabilize the climate rise to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - the company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all-new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they do not contain any mercury.
A number of specialists have reported reservations for compact fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and they need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set guidelines.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion dollars.
