Avengers and Spies in Diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals itself as an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file constituted by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The “extraordinary” U.S. revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits only report what could be read in any newspaper for months (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi’s sinisterly caricatured profile has long been for sketchy cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (or know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occultism believe only in what they already know, and which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (otherwise he might be, I know, editor at Liberation), who holds as true only what he acknowledges.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have turned into centers of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put U.S. diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put so much the victims in crisis as the “bullies”.
But let’s get to the deep nature of what happened.
In the days of Orwell, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had proved completely since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken, and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel was already saying, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that all knowing about Berlusconi’s or Merkel’s character is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from her.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - that would be to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it's just as obvious that with today's technologies, it's useless to hope to be able to keep confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state travelled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in single copies in locked drawers: deep down, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired telegraph.
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and uncovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now the (digital) CDs only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communication policy and technology should come back to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secrecy of the embassies.
Now, it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacks its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to consider whether the promises of fast-start or early-stage financing made by developed countries are being met.
And the big French doughnuts are revealed.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU released the big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU said it had made €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment in terms of "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their calculation method.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 lent equals €1 given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is false to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, only the cost of the loan for the lender country should be counted under its commitments (equivalent of interest).
But France has nothing to do with such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so heavily.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts in €1 to meet its commitment, France puts in only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice pass-through tour!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it can make believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy did the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward the discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the way of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
