Warning for pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly the Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and a snack in a day by a child of a decade, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as treats, were tested by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The bottom line is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies from several institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our investigation clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three proven as certain carcinogens, as well as nearly twenty residues that can disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were packed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of this “contaminant cocktail” “is probably underestimated,” according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "facing the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase of diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
